Fitelson-Otter Branch -- Resonators and Ancestor Subsumption
=============================================================

This branch adds two opt-in features ported from Otter to Prover9, both
motivated by Fitelson, "Clause Weighting and the Resonance Strategy:
Otter, Prover9, and the Loss of Resonators" (April 2026).  Both features
are OFF by default.  Neither touches the default inference calculus;
both are strictly additive and leave existing input decks unaffected.


Background
----------

Otter supported two facilities that did not survive into Prover9:

  1. Wos-style RESONATORS -- weight templates in which every variable
     occurrence is an independent wildcard matching any subterm, with
     no binding consistency across occurrences.  Resonators implement
     Wos's resonance strategy: shape-based (functional-skeleton-based)
     search direction, distinct from hints.

  2. ANCESTOR SUBSUMPTION -- a refinement of ordinary subsumption that
     preserves short-proof variants when two clauses are alphabetic
     variants but differ in derivation length.  Useful for proof
     shortening and iterative resonance/hint pipelines.

Both were lost in Prover9's redesign: its equational weight rules use
binding variable matching, making Wos-style resonators inexpressible;
and its subsumption has no proof-cost tie-breaker.  This branch
restores both, keeping Prover9's existing mechanisms unchanged when
the new features are not used.


Feature A: list(resonators)
---------------------------

Syntax:

    list(resonators).
      weight( PATTERN, N ).
      weight( PATTERN, N ).
      ...
    end_of_list.

PATTERN is an ordinary term (or literal).  N is an integer weight
assigned to any clause whose functional skeleton matches the pattern.

Matching semantics (Wos):

  - Every variable occurrence in PATTERN -- named (x, y, A, ...) or
    anonymous (_, _1..._9) -- is an INDEPENDENT wildcard.  It matches
    ANY subterm (variable OR complex term).  There is no binding
    consistency: two occurrences of "x" in a single pattern are not
    required to match the same subterm.
  - Non-variable symbols must match structurally (same symbol, same
    arity, recursive argument match).

Examples:

    weight( i(x, x), 2 ).
      matches P(i(a, b)), P(i(f(g), h)), P(i(a, a)) -- anything
      whose argument to i is a two-argument structure, regardless of
      whether the two argument positions hold the same subterm.

    weight( x * y = y * x, 0 ).
      matches any equation A*B = C*D for any subterms A,B,C,D --
      which captures commutativity in any form, whatever the terms.

    weight( x * (y * z) = (x * y) * z, 0 ).
      matches any equation of associativity shape, even when the
      subterms are complex.

Role (Otter pick_and_purge parity):

  - Resonators are consulted BEFORE ordinary weight rules (those in
    list(weights)).  First-match-wins across the resonator list.
  - A matching clause receives the resonator's weight in place of its
    symbol-count weight.  Low-weight resonators (e.g. weight 0) give
    high selection priority AND protect against SOS-size eviction --
    Otter's pick_and_purge behavior.
  - Existing list(weights) rules still apply to clauses that match
    no resonator.

Soundness:

  - Resonators affect only weight assignment.  They do not change
    inference rules or subsumption.  Any soundness/completeness
    caveats that already applied to Prover9's weighting (e.g.,
    max_weight/SOS-limit eviction) apply unchanged; no new risk class
    is introduced.


Feature B: set(ancestor_subsume)
--------------------------------

Syntax:

    set(ancestor_subsume).   % off by default
    set(proof_weight).       % off by default; selects tie-break metric

Behavior:

When ancestor_subsume is on, before clause C is allowed to subsume
clause D (whether via forward or back subsumption), we apply the
following refinement:

  - If D also subsumes C (i.e. C and D are alphabetic variants), we
    compare derivation costs.  The subsumption proceeds only if
    cost(C) <= cost(D); otherwise D is kept, and the subsumption is
    blocked.  Stats.anc_subsume_blocked counts these events.
  - Otherwise (C is strictly more general), the subsumption proceeds
    unconditionally.

Two cost metrics:

  - proof_weight OFF (default): cost is proof_length(c) = number of
    distinct ancestors of c in the proof DAG.
  - proof_weight ON: cost is proof_tree_weight(c) = number of
    input-clause leaves in the proof TREE of c (shared ancestors
    counted with multiplicity).  This corresponds to Otter's
    set(proof_weight) metric.

Soundness:

  - Ancestor subsumption only ever BLOCKS subsumptions -- it retains
    more clauses, never fewer.  Keeping redundant clauses is always
    sound and preserves refutational completeness.  The cost is
    search performance, never correctness.


